omen, to access wages and self-employment in the apiculture industry through skill development and financial support.\r\n\r\na€œHoneybees play multifunctional roles beyond the production of honey, beeswax, and other hive products, and deliver vital insect pollination services to food and industrial crops, forages, forest trees, and other plant biodiversity, a€œ says Zerihun Lemma Damenu, IIRR Ethiopia Country Director. a€œThe MaYEA project uses integrated beekeeping as an entry point to sustainably improve our rural communities by generating dignified jobs and contributing to the regeneration of the natural environment.a€\u009d\r\n\r\nThe overarching objective of the 5-year program is to triple current annual honey production by 2028, achieved through the recruitment of 300,000 new beekeepers, increased productivity among 350,000 existing young beekeeping farmers, and the engagement of an additional 350,000 young individuals in integrated value chain activities.\r\n\r\nRecognizing the potential of the Ethiopian apiculture sector to generate up to four million employment opportunities, MaYEA addresses existing challenges to economic opportunities, including skill gaps, low production volume and quality, limited value addition, inadequate market infrastructure, and weak regulatory frameworks. To address these issues, the program adopts a multi-faceted transformative approach encompassing improved beekeeping technologies, digital advancements, capacity building, and access to finance and markets.\r\n\r\nThis initiative holds promise to increase honey and beeswax production and improve quality, promote market-driven value addition, enhance integration with complementary value chains, and foster an enabling environment for youth and apiculture sector development. \r\n\r\nAlongside our implementing partners, we embark on this journey with a commitment to fostering economic sustainability, youth empowerment, and poverty alleviation for young people across Ethiopia.\r\n\r\n