e through work and balancing that with the studies .\r\n\r\nWhat differences do you find between academic learning and hands-on experience in your apprenticeship?\r\nIts good to have those study days and getting that theory aspect in, however being a kinaesthetic learner I have learnt most of the apprenticeship while working in my role and wished I was able to work 5 days.\r\n\r\nWhat do you consider the pros of an apprenticeship?\r\nIt is a fantastic option for young eager, learners that is a perfect option for university and college and I am a huge supporter of apprenticeships and should be allowed within the education curriculum.\r\n\r\nHow do you balance working and studying in your apprenticeship?\r\nThe structured lessons, tutorials and knowing which days I was studying in advanced allowed me to plan ahead and not loose track.\r\n\r\nWhat advice would you give to someone considering an apprenticeship or similar path?\r\nIf youa€™re aged between 18-24 this is the perfect opportunity to take up. My advice is take your time, speak up and ask for help and most importantly make sure you are organised like no one else.\r\n\r\n#NAW2024 #Apprenticeships\r\n\\uD83C\\uDF27 Research shows poor employee health is estimated to cost the UK economy A£138 billion per year. \r\n\r\n\\uD83D\\uDCC5 And the majority of lost working hours aren't due to formal absence - they're down to presenteeism. On average, UK employees take 6 sick leave days per year, but actually lose an additional 43 days due to overlooking their physical and mental ill health. \r\n\r\n\\uD83D\\uDD0E What's more, this is particularly profound in employees under 30. Whilst younger employees report to have better physical health, they have significantly higher levels of mental health concerns including burnout, depression and fatigue. \r\n\r\n\\uD83C\\uDF31 In 2024 businesses must make proactive strides to close the widening gap between what teams need and the support currently provided. To empower all talent 