nd container ships in particular the number of large box ships idled fell to zero with carriers deploying tonnage to maintain schedules on the longer Cape route. Diversions around the Cape of Good Hope began in December as the Houthi Movement fired on Israeli-bound, US and British connected vessels and Alphaliner reports that the rush to fulfil exports before Chinese New Year, these week long celebrations begin tomorrow. All ships larger than 12,500 TEUs are now deployed a€œfollowing the reactivation of two ultra-large container ships to service over the past fortnight,a€\u009d reported Alphaliner.\r\n\r\nAfter its latest survey completed on 29 January. Idled capacity has reached a 19-month low, at 89 ships of 226,051 TEUs, and the idled figure may have fallen even further in the last week with the latest figure from Linerlytica showing just 78 non-operational ships totaling 125,425 TEUs, 0.4% of the fleet. a€œCarriers are starting to redesign their networks to incorporate the diversion via Africa, together with the expected skipped sailings in the slack period after Chinese New Year and the arrival of many large new buildings, this situation of tight tonnage supply might change in the coming months,a€\u009d said Alphaliner.\r\n\r\nA fact that Linerlytica can confirm with its latest report signaling a further 43 ships delivered in the last 30 days, totaling 303,601 TEUs. The combined statistics also reveal an expected surge of capacity on the Asia to Europe trades of 23.3%, when compared to last yeara€™s deployment, reaching an all-time high of 6.44 million TEUs. This rush to deploy capacity is entirely a result of the diversion from the Suez to the Cape route since December 2023. a€œOver 700,000 TEUs of additional capacity has been added to the trade in the last two months alone. 55% of the additional capacity has been absorbed in the Far East-Mediterranean trades where transit times have increased by 10 days to the West Med and 18 days to the East Med while transit times to North Europe has increased by seven days on average,a€\u009d said Linerlyticaa€™s analysis.\r\n\r\nSource:Container News \r\n\r\nWe believe in an inclusive energyA transition to a net-zero future.A EmbeddingA human rights, creatingA working environments where ourA people can thrive, and havingA aA positive impact in the communitiesA where we operateA guide our actionsA to promote social progress.a€‹\r\na€‹\r\nLearn more about ourA initiativesA around theA world: https://lnkd.in/eEqc-Ueh\r\n\r\n#energytransitiona€‹ #technology #sustainability\r\n\\uD83C\\uDF1FDid you know that 75% of all the aluminium ever produced is still in productive use? a™»i¸\u008f This statistic from the International Aluminium Institute highlights the importance of sustainability in the industry and showcases the durability and recyclability of this versatile metal. Join us in embracing a greener future! \\uD83C\\uDF0D \\uD83D\\uDC4F\\uD83C\\uDFFC#OneStepGreener #Sustainability #HillsNumberplates\r\nEarlier this week our Chief Executive Melissa Kittermaster and our senior analysts George Day and Tilly White-Christmas exhibited at the Institute of Government & Public Policy's Energy and Sustainability Conference. It was great to be involved in the event and get the opportunity to listen to some fantastic talks from our industry peers. Following the event our team have put together a list of 5 key takeaways from the event that we think are going to be important for all organisations to remember going forward. Check out our article below!\r\n\r\n#igppENERGY #sustainability #conference2024 #netzerotransition #netzero #transitionplanning \r\n\r\nJoshua Rogerson\r\nInsights from ACCESS 2024 Conference\r\nA \r\nHere are some impressions from ACCESS 2024 in Miami, where Brian Gavin and Brad Groves led a pre-conference short course on market access trends and opportunities in the European landscape.\r\nA \r\n\\uD83D\\uDD0D Some of the key themes covered included:\r\nA \r\n1. Dynamic Trends: