l communities. \r\n\r\na€œSmall business owners are exposed to an array of challenges a€“ from securing funding in a tough economic environment to developing new products while trying to scale,a€\u009d said Lorraine Deschamps, EMEA Head of Corporate Social Responsibility. a€œThe Back2Business programme enables diverse-owned businesses in the U.K. to grow while celebrating their achievements. Fiserv is delighted to back a number of local entrepreneurs, and support job creation and economic development in the local area.a€\u009d\r\n\r\nSince 2020, Back2Business from Fiserv has awarded more than 1,800 grants to minority-, women-, veteran-, LGBTQ+- and ethnically diverse-owned businesses in the U.S. and U.K.\r\n\r\nCongratulations to our newest grantees a€“ and thank you for creating positive and lasting impact in your communities and beyond!\r\n\r\n#NationalEntrepreneurshipWeek #FlashbackFriday #FiservProud\r\nLast week, I had the privilege of joining thought leaders at the #POC2024 conference in Kuala Lumpur. My recent move to Singapore has meant that Ia€™m increasingly working with clients within the #palmoil sector, so it was enlightening to hear from influential industry figures, academics, and economists on the industry's prospective challenges and opportunities in the year ahead.\r\n\r\nHere are some of my key insights from the conference:\r\nA \r\nEU's Deforestation Regulation & Smallholder InclusionA \\uD83E\\uDDD1a€\u008d\\uD83C\\uDF3E\\uD83C\\uDF34 \r\nThe dialogue around the EU's Deforestation Regulation, particularly viewed through a non-Western lens, was eye-opening. The discourse focused on the gap between policy intentions and on-the-ground realities. A poignant issue that continued to be raised was whether smallholders could effectively adapt to the #EUDR directives in time without jeopardising their place in global supply chains. For me, the conversation underscored the necessity of globally inclusive policy-making that incorporates stakeholders at every supply chain level. \r\nA \r\nComparison with Other Agri-commoditiesA \\uD83C\\uDF31 \r\nConversation noted that palm oil's #sustainability advancements are commendable, especially compared to commodities like cocoa, soy, and rubber. The sector has made significant progress in certification and\r\ndeforestation reduction, presenting a valuable opportunity for cross-sector\r\nknowledge exchange to enhance sustainability practices industry-wide.\r\nA \r\nDigitalisation and AutomationA \\uD83E\\uDD16 \r\nThe surge of #digitalisation and #automation themes indicated a strong belief in the transformative power of technology. Investments in this area have the potential to reverse declining yields and inject resilience into production operations.\r\nA \r\nSustainability as a Growth Factor\\uD83C\\uDF43 \r\nDespite the price-focused nature of the conference, sustainability emerged as a core discussion point. It was intriguing to observe it characterised as both an industry hurdle and a catalyst for inclusive growth and market expansion.\r\nA \r\nBiofuels and Market DynamicsA aœˆ \r\nIn-depth sessions on biofuels highlighted the palm oil sector's ambition to serve as a feedstock for the aviation industry despite current restrictions in EU and US markets. The conversation advocated for greater regional market utilisation and stressed the palm industry's need to be a more proactive participant in shaping #biofuel policies. Additionally, advocacy for recognising Asia Pacific's sustainable advancements was seen as essential to dismantling current barriers.\r\nA \r\nPalm Oil Supply OutlookA \\uD83D\\uDCC9 \r\nA forecast that surprised me was the anticipated slowdown in palm oil supply. Factors contributing to this slowdown include geopolitical strife, surging production costs, the age of plantations, and climate impacts like El NiA±o.\r\nA \r\nThese takeaways reflect the conference's depth and diversity of perspectives. I'm eager to continue working on these complex issues and supporting my clients in navigating them.\r\nWe are delighted to announce that we will exhibit at the NMBS show this year!\r\n\r\nThe event is held at the Coventry Building Society Arena on April 10th and 11th.\r\n\r\nThe exhibition is for merchants to meet existing and new manufacturers and distributors with discounts and promotions only available to NMBS members who attend the show aœ” \r\n\r\nIf you would like more information on the show, you can click the link below.\r\n\r\n- https://lnkd.in/dMwBtrAp\r\nAnd we are off: E-world energy & water 2024!\r\n\r\nThe E-world energy & water is the place where the European energy industry comes together. Key topics are the energy transition, tomorrow's heat supply and the security of supply and demand.\r\n\r\nOur Energy Experts are here to discuss with you these and other topics.\r\n\r\nWe are looking forward to meeting you at our stand Hall 3, Number 3G115.A Visit us! \r\n\r\n#SustainabilityA #energyA #eworld2024A\r\nApis Partners is pleased to announce that Co-Founder and Managing Partner, Udayan Goyal, will be speaking at the upcoming GPC Conference, organised by the Global Private Capital Association in partnership with the IFC - International Finance Corporation.\r\n\r\n\\uD83D\\uDCC6: 27th March 2024\r\n\\uD83D\\uDD59: 10:10AM - 10:50AM ('The Evolution of Impact Investing')\r\n\\uD83D\\uDCCC: New York\r\n\r\nFor more information and to register for the event, click here: https://lnkd.in/eUURpkP4 \r\n\r\n#GPCC24 #PrivateCapital #ImpactInvesting\r\nWhat does the #officeofthefuture look like? We think it will look a lot like 4 Hardman Square, our iconic office in Spinningfields, Manchester, which we are currently repositioning to reflect the ways in which people want to work post-pandemic. \r\n\r\nOn completion, expected by the end of this year, the building will offer best in class Grade-A space that combines contemporary design with environmental responsibility. All 55,000 sq ft of space will be upgraded, with a new